\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $O\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be an open set.
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{c}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 be a limit point of 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Then every neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 contains some point of 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{c}$
\end_inset

.
 But this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 cannot be in the open set 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in O$
\end_inset

 implies there exists a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\epsilon}(x)\subseteq O$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in O^{c}$
\end_inset

, as desired.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{c}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in O$
\end_inset

 be arbitrary; we want to produce an 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

-neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\epsilon}(x)\subseteq O$
\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{c}$
\end_inset

 is closed, we can be sure that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
a limit point of 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, by definition, there must be some neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\epsilon}(x)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that does not intersect the set 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{c}$
\end_inset

.
 But this means 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\epsilon}(x)\subseteq O$
\end_inset

, as desired.
\end_layout

