\begin_layout Definition
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
bounded
\series default
 if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $M>0$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $|a|\leq M$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
compact 
\series default
if it satisfies 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generalized B-W
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: every sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{n})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\in K$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 has a subsequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{n_{k}})$
\end_inset

 converging to some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem

\series bold
(Characterization of Compactness in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

) 
\series default
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is compact if and only if it is closed and bounded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 Exercise 3.3.3, unclaimed HW.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be compact and assume for contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is unbounded.
 We'll produce a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 that marches off to 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 in such a way that it can't have a convergent subsequence.
 To do this, notice that because 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is unbounded, there exists an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\in K$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $|x_{1}|>1$
\end_inset

.
 Likewise, there must exist 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}\in K$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|x_{2}|>2$
\end_inset

, and in general, given 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, we can produce 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in K$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $|x_{n}|>n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now, because 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be compact, 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 should have a convergent subsequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n_{k}})$
\end_inset

.
 But the elements of the subsequence must satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $|x_{n_{k}}|>n_{k}$
\end_inset

, and consequently 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n_{k}})$
\end_inset

 is unbounded.
 Because convergent sequences are bounded, we have a contradiction.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 must be a bounded set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now, we'll show that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is also closed.
 To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 contains its limit points, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\lim x_{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and argue that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

 as well.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is bounded, so is 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

, and by B-W, 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 must have a subsequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n_{k}})$
\end_inset

 converging to some limit 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is compact, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Since subsequences of convergent sequences converge to the same limit,
 it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})\to x\in K$
\end_inset

 as well.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is closed.
\end_layout

